    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I would propose that you don't need to send a signal just for the timer end. You could just do the processing/fetching that we call on the Nim side, then those send their own signals that Nim already knows how to process.\r\n\r\npro: it's cleaner and we have less signal handling to do. Nim doesn't even have to know about the timer\r\n\r\ncon: it's a semi-breaking change. Mobile would then be \"double\" fetching the history for example. Also, maybe mobile doesn't want to fetch as often?\r\n  - One solution for that would be to add a new setting (or similar) that you can send the amount of time you want to set the timer, so basically the fetching interval. That solves both issues. Mobile can set a higher interval if they want. Also, we make that setting `null` or `undefined` by default, so we only perform the timer/interval when it is not null. That way, the status-go timer would only work on desktop until mobile updates their own wallet code.",
